{
    "level": "B2",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn <strong>complex passive constructions with infinitives and gerunds</strong>. These are the key forms for academic, scientific and formal writing.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "to be done",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "<strong>Passive infinitive</strong> - present/future:",
            "example": "The report needs to be finished."
        },
        {
            "label": "being done",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "<strong>Passive gerund</strong> is a process:",
            "example": "She hates being interrupted."
        },
        {
            "label": "having been done",
            "color": "rose",
            "text": "<strong>Perfect passive gerund</strong> - previous action:",
            "example": "Having been warned, he was careful."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Three basic passive forms",
    "intro": "Comparison of three key designs:",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "to be + V3",
            "title": "Passive infinitive",
            "subtitle": "Present/future action in the passive"
        },
        {
            "label": "to have been + V3",
            "title": "Perfect passive infinitive",
            "subtitle": "Previous action completed before speaking"
        },
        {
            "label": "being + V3",
            "title": "Passive gerund",
            "subtitle": "Process, ongoing action in the passive"
        },
        {
            "label": "having been + V3",
            "title": "Perfect passive gerund",
            "subtitle": "An action that preceded another"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. To be done is a passive infinitive",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Structure",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "<strong>to be + Past Participle (V3)</strong>. Used after many verbs and in modal constructions.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The report needs to be finished by Friday.",
                    "ua": "The report needs to be finished by Friday."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I want to be informed immediately.",
                    "ua": "I want to be informed immediately."
                },
                {
                    "en": "This task has to be completed today.",
                    "ua": "This task has to be completed today."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "After the verbs seem, appear",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "After <strong>seem, appear, happen, turn out</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He appears to be well respected.",
                    "ua": "He appears to be well respected."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The meeting seems to be postponed.",
                    "ua": "The meeting seems to be postponed."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She happened to be chosen for the role.",
                    "ua": "She happened to be chosen for the role."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "After want, expect, would like",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "When someone wants <strong>something done</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I want this issue to be resolved.",
                    "ua": "I want this issue to be resolved."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They expect the project to be approved.",
                    "ua": "They expect the project to be approved."
                },
                {
                    "en": "We would like the order to be delivered.",
                    "ua": "We would like the order to be delivered."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. To have been done is a perfect passive infinitive",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Structure",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "<strong>to have been + V3</strong>. Indicates an action that <strong>happened before</strong> relative to the moment of speech.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He seems to have been promoted.",
                    "ua": "He seems to have been promoted."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The documents appear to have been lost.",
                    "ua": "The documents appear to have been lost."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She claims to have been invited.",
                    "ua": "She claims to have been invited."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Reporting structures",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "In impersonal passive constructions for <strong>assumptions about the past</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He is believed to have been kidnapped.",
                    "ua": "He is believed to have been kidnapped."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The painting is thought to have been stolen.",
                    "ua": "The painting is thought to have been stolen."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She is reported to have been seen in Paris.",
                    "ua": "She is reported to have been seen in Paris."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "After modals + have",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "After <strong>must have, could have, should have</strong> - assumptions about the past.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The email must have been sent.",
                    "ua": "The email must have been sent."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The mistake could have been avoided.",
                    "ua": "The mistake could have been avoided."
                },
                {
                    "en": "This should have been done earlier.",
                    "ua": "This should have been done earlier."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Being done is a passive gerund",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Structure",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "<strong>being + V3</strong>. Used after prepositions and verbs that require a gerund.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She hates being interrupted.",
                    "ua": "She hates being interrupted."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I remember being taught this rule.",
                    "ua": "I remember being taught this rule."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He denied being involved in the incident.",
                    "ua": "He denied being involved in the incident."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "After prepositions",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "Після <strong>without, after, before, on, by, despite</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He left without being noticed.",
                    "ua": "He left without being noticed."
                },
                {
                    "en": "After being rejected, she tried again.",
                    "ua": "After being rejected, she tried again."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Despite being warned, he continued.",
                    "ua": "Despite being warned, he continued."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "After like, enjoy, avoid",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "After verbs requiring <strong>-ing forms</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Nobody likes being criticized.",
                    "ua": "Nobody likes being criticized."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He enjoys being praised.",
                    "ua": "He enjoys being praised."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She avoids being seen in public.",
                    "ua": "She avoids being seen in public."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "5. Having been done is a perfect passive gerund",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Structure",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "<strong>having been + V3</strong>. For actions that <strong>preceded others</strong> (cause → effect).",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Having been warned, he was more careful.",
                    "ua": "Having been warned, he was more careful."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Having been told the truth, she felt relieved.",
                    "ua": "Having been told the truth, she felt relieved."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Having been approved, the project will begin.",
                    "ua": "Having been approved, the project will begin."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Formal style",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "Often in <strong>academic, official</strong> and written speech.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Having been elected, she took office.",
                    "ua": "Having been elected, she took office."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Having been reviewed, the document was signed.",
                    "ua": "Having been reviewed, the document was signed."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Having been trained properly, the team succeeded.",
                    "ua": "Having been trained properly, the team succeeded."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "After verbs of memory",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "After <strong>remember, regret, deny, admit</strong>.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She regrets having been so rude.",
                    "ua": "She regrets having been so rude."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He admits having been mistaken.",
                    "ua": "He admits having been mistaken."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I remember having been told about this.",
                    "ua": "I remember having been told about this."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "6. The most frequent patterns of use",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Need/want/require + to be done",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "<strong>Need/want/require + to be + V3</strong> - the need to perform.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "This problem needs to be solved.",
                    "ua": "This problem needs to be solved."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The contract needs to be signed.",
                    "ua": "The contract needs to be signed."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The issue requires to be addressed.",
                    "ua": "The issue requires to be addressed."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "seem/appear + to be done",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "<strong>Seem/appear + to be + V3</strong> — impression, guess.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The door seems to be locked.",
                    "ua": "The door seems to be locked."
                },
                {
                    "en": "He appears to be respected by everyone.",
                    "ua": "He appears to be respected by everyone."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "is said/believed + to be/have been",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "<strong>Reporting passive</strong> — reports, rumors.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He is said to be a genius.",
                    "ua": "He is said to be a genius."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She is believed to have left the country.",
                    "ua": "She is believed to have left the country."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "hate/like/enjoy + being done",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "<strong>Feeling verbs + being + V3</strong> — reaction to an action.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "She hates being ignored.",
                    "ua": "She hates being ignored."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Children love being praised.",
                    "ua": "Children love being praised."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "7. Summary table of forms",
    "intro": "Comparison of all passive forms with infinitives and gerunds:",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "to be + V3",
            "ua": "to be + V3",
            "note": "The work needs to be done."
        },
        {
            "en": "to have been + V3",
            "ua": "to have been + V3",
            "note": "He seems to have been promoted."
        },
        {
            "en": "being + V3",
            "ua": "being + V3",
            "note": "She hates being interrupted."
        },
        {
            "en": "having been + V3",
            "ua": "having been + V3",
            "note": "Having been warned, he left."
        }
    ],
    "warning": "📌 <strong>Perfect forms</strong> (to have been, having been) indicate an action that preceded another!"
}

{
    "title": "8. Typical mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Error 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Confusion to be done and being done.",
            "wrong": "I enjoy to be praised.",
            "right": "✅ I enjoy being praised."
        },
        {
            "label": "Error 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Skip been in perfect forms.",
            "wrong": "He seems to have promoted.",
            "right": "✅ He seems to have been promoted."
        },
        {
            "label": "Error 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Incorrect word order.",
            "wrong": "Having warned been, he was careful.",
            "right": "✅ Having been warned, he was careful."
        },
        {
            "label": "Error 4",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Active form instead of passive.",
            "wrong": "The report needs finishing.",
            "right": "✅ The report needs to be finished."
        }
    ]
}
